    <a title="Nigeyb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10301421-nigeyb"><img alt="Nigeyb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593065725p2/10301421.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4102955118?book_show_action=true">Jul 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nigeyb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nigeyb" href="/user/show/10301421-nigeyb">Nigeyb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780755358793" href="/book/show/18399837-instructions-for-a-heatwave">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4102955118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6832098873195481597"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16077150.Instructions_for_a_Heatwave' title='Instructions for a Heatwave by Maggie O&apos;Farrell' rel='nofollow noopener'>Instructions for a Heatwave</a> (2013) by <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/91236.Maggie_O_Farrell' title='Maggie O&apos;Farrell' rel='nofollow noopener'>Maggie O&apos;Farrell</a> is set in London during the heatwave of summer 1976. In the third month of the drought that bakes the city, a devoted husband and father goes out to buy a newspaper but doesn&apos;t come back. There is nothing obvious to suggest why he might have disappeared, although his wife seems to know more than she is letting on. This mystery is at the heart of the novel. <br/><br/>The disappeared father&apos;s three grown up children all have complicated lives and back s</span>
  <span id="freeText6832098873195481597" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16077150.Instructions_for_a_Heatwave" title="Instructions for a Heatwave by Maggie O'Farrell" rel="nofollow noopener">Instructions for a Heatwave</a> (2013) by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/91236.Maggie_O_Farrell" title="Maggie O'Farrell" rel="nofollow noopener">Maggie O'Farrell</a> is set in London during the heatwave of summer 1976. In the third month of the drought that bakes the city, a devoted husband and father goes out to buy a newspaper but doesn't come back. There is nothing obvious to suggest why he might have disappeared, although his wife seems to know more than she is letting on. This mystery is at the heart of the novel. <br><br>The disappeared father's three grown up children all have complicated lives and back stories and so, in addition to the mystery of the disappearance, there are three additional narrative strands. These separate stories are all deftly handled and overall this is an enjoyable novel.<br><br>That said, whilst competently written, there is no sense of real mystery, jeopardy or tension. It was obvious everything would be resolved happily and the Hollywood ending felt both predictable and underwhelming. Also the heatwave, foregrounded at first and presumably a metaphor for oppression, gradually recedes, a bit like the novel's early promise.<br><br>3/5<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1380897714l/18399837.jpg" width="180" height="280" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>It’s July 1976. In London, it hasn’t rained for months, gardens are filled with aphids, water comes from a standpipe, and Robert Riordan tells his wife Gretta that he’s going round the corner to buy a newspaper. He doesn’t come back.<br><br>The search for Robert brings Gretta’s children – two estranged sisters and a brother on the brink of divorce – back home, each with different ideas as to where their father might have gone. None of them suspects that their mother might have an explanation that even now she cannot share.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="6832098873195481597" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
