<div id="review_2409590419" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2409590419" />
    <a title="Lydia Bailey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45167722-lydia-bailey"><img alt="Lydia Bailey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541061199p2/45167722.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2409590419?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lydia Bailey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lydia Bailey" href="/user/show/45167722-lydia-bailey">Lydia Bailey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2409590419" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6481903359753295493">I read this straight off the back of three amazing novels (a Sally Rooney and two by Patrick Gale) so this one had a lot to live up to, but I have really enjoyed it. It’s only the second Maggie O’Farrell novel I’ve read and I much preferred this to The Distance Between Us. The blurb tells us that in the middle of the 1976 heatwave in London, Gretta’s husband, Robert, pops to the paper shop early one morning and never returns. It is known that he’s not met with a sticky end but no one can find hi</span>
  <span id="freeText6481903359753295493" style="display:none">I read this straight off the back of three amazing novels (a Sally Rooney and two by Patrick Gale) so this one had a lot to live up to, but I have really enjoyed it. It’s only the second Maggie O’Farrell novel I’ve read and I much preferred this to The Distance Between Us. The blurb tells us that in the middle of the 1976 heatwave in London, Gretta’s husband, Robert, pops to the paper shop early one morning and never returns. It is known that he’s not met with a sticky end but no one can find him. As it transpires, the book isn’t really about that at all (and disturbingly no one seems particularly alarmed at a much loved Dad going missing) but about the family politics, personalities and histories of Robert and Gretta’s three adult children; the siblings who come together to find him. <br /><br />The resulting scenario is a little hard to believe (but then again people can be odd) &amp; the author concentrates so much on the main characters’ flaws, rather than their strengths, that they are hard to love. <br />However, they are very human &amp; believable characters and it’s a really interesting journey through family dynamics. A good read which I throughly enjoyed. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6481903359753295493" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


